						               													<description>Rather than go to war, the indigenous tribes of Chelonia have invented a novel way of settling disputes. As my learned reader will no doubt be aware, Chelonia is the last remaining habitat of Proganochelys quenstedti, the roof turtle; now hunted to extinction elsewhere because of its colourful shell. The natives play a game on the backs of the turtles, which is described below. Naturally, the game must be played quickly before the affronted turtle reaches the water and swims off.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In Turtle Thumb Tussle, two players use their hands to occupy territory on a board resembling a turtle's shell.  Players roll dice to determine which finger moves next, and to what colour.  Think Twister meets Sumo with hands instead of bodies, and you won't be far off the mark!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
